🔹 Topic: Angular Basics Every Interviewer Expects

1️⃣ What is Angular?
Angular is a TypeScript-based frontend framework developed by Google for building scalable, 
single-page applications (SPAs) using a component-based architecture.
_____________________________________________________________________________

2️⃣ What are the key building blocks of Angular?
 • Modules – organize application features
 • Components – control views and UI logic
 • Templates – HTML with Angular syntax
 • Services – reusable business logic
 • Dependency Injection (DI) – provides dependencies efficiently
_____________________________________________________________________________

3️⃣ What is a Component?
A component is the core UI building block in Angular.
It consists of:
 • HTML template
 • TypeScript class
 • CSS styles

Each component controls a specific part of the UI.
_________________________________________________________________________________________

4️⃣ What is Data Binding in Angular?
Data binding synchronizes data between the component class and the template.

Types:
 • Interpolation {{ }} // Ex:{{ title }}
   One-way data binding from component to template
 • Property binding [ ] // Ex: [src]="imageUrl"
   One-way data binding from component to DOM element
 • Event binding ( ) // Ex: (click)="handleClick()"
   One-way data binding from DOM element to component
 • Two-way binding [(ngModel)] // Ex: [(ngModel)]="username"
   Two-way data binding between component and DOM element
________________________________________________________________________________________

5️⃣ Why is Angular suitable for large applications?
 • Strong structure and conventions
 • Built-in DI and RxJS
 • Powerful CLI
 • Easy to scale and maintain

 Angular Lifecycle Hooks

Continuing the Angular Day-wise Interview Series, focusing on a topic that almost every Angular interview touches.
_____________________________________________________________________________

🔹 What is an Angular Module?
An Angular module (NgModule) is used to group related components, directives, pipes, and services into a single unit.
It helps with:
• Code organization
• Feature separation
• Lazy loading
_____________________________________________________________________________
🔹 Types of Angular Modules
• Root module (AppModule)
• Feature modules
• Shared modules
• Core modules
_____________________________________________________________________________
🔹 What are Standalone Components?
Standalone components (Angular 14+) allow creating components without NgModules.
They can directly import dependencies like:
• CommonModule
• FormsModule
• Other standalone components
_____________________________________________________________________________
🔹 Benefits of Standalone Components
• Less boilerplate
• Faster learning curve
• Better tree-shaking
• Simplified architecture
_____________________________________________________________________________
🔹 NgModule vs Standalone Components
NgModule:
• More boilerplate
• Required before Angular 14
• Good for large legacy apps
Standalone Components:
• Minimal setup
• Modern Angular approach
• Recommended for new applications

💡 Interview Tip
Angular is moving towards standalone-first architecture. Knowing when and how to use it is a strong plus in interviews.
___________________________________________________________________________________________________________________
🔹 Topic: Angular Lifecycle Hooks

1️⃣ What are Angular lifecycle hooks?
Lifecycle hooks are methods that allow you to tap into different phases of a component’s 
life—from creation to destruction.
_____________________________________________________________________________

2️⃣ Most commonly used lifecycle hooks?
 • ngOnInit()
Called once after component initialization.
👉 Best place for API calls and initial setup.
 • ngOnChanges()
Triggered when @Input() values change.
👉 Used when a component reacts to parent data changes.
 • ngAfterViewInit()
Called after the component’s view is fully initialized.
👉 Useful for DOM access and ViewChild logic.
 • ngOnDestroy()
Called before the component is destroyed.
👉 Cleanup subscriptions, timers, event listeners.
_____________________________________________________________________________

3️⃣ Difference between constructor and ngOnInit()?
 • constructor → used for dependency injection
 • ngOnInit() → used for component initialization logic
_____________________________________________________________________________

4️⃣ Why is ngOnDestroy() important?
Failing to clean up subscriptions can lead to memory leaks and performance issues.
_____________________________________________________________________________

5️⃣ Interview Tip 💡
Interviewers often ask:
👉 “Where do you unsubscribe from observables?”
✔️ Correct answer: ngOnDestroy()
_____________________________________________________________________________________

🔹Topic: Change Detection in Angular

1️⃣ What is Change Detection?
Change Detection is the mechanism Angular uses to sync data changes with the UI.
Whenever application state changes, Angular checks components and updates the DOM if needed.
____________________________________________________________________________________

2️⃣ How does Angular trigger change detection?
Change detection runs on:
 • User events (click, input)
 • HTTP responses
 • Timers (setTimeout, setInterval)
 • Promises & Observables

👉 Powered by Zone.js
____________________________________________________________________________________

3️⃣ What is Default Change Detection strategy?
 • Angular checks all components in the component tree
 • Simple but can cause performance issues in large apps
____________________________________________________________________________________

4️⃣ What is OnPush Change Detection?
OnPush tells Angular to run change detection only when:
 • @Input() reference changes
 • An event occurs inside the component
 • An observable emits (via async pipe)

📌 This significantly improves performance.
____________________________________________________________________________________

5️⃣ When should you use OnPush?
 • Large applications
 • Components with immutable data
 • Reusable / presentational components
____________________________________________________________________________________

6️⃣ Common interview follow-up 💡
👉 Why doesn’t UI update with OnPush?
✔️ Because object reference didn’t change — Angular relies on immutability.
__________________________________________________________________________________

🔹Topic: Angular Directives

1️⃣ What is a Directive in Angular?
A directive is a class that adds behavior to existing DOM elements or changes how elements are rendered.
____________________________________________________________________________________

2️⃣ Types of Directives in Angular
 • Component Directives
Components themselves are directives with a template.
 • Structural Directives
Change the DOM structure by adding/removing elements.
Examples: *ngIf, *ngFor, *ngSwitch
 • Attribute Directives
Change the appearance or behavior of an element.
Examples: ngClass, ngStyle, custom directives
____________________________________________________________________________________

3️⃣ Key difference: Structural vs Attribute Directives
 • Structural → prefixed with *, modify DOM layout
 • Attribute → applied as attributes, modify element behavior
____________________________________________________________________________________

4️⃣ Why does Angular allow only one structural directive per element?
Because each structural directive manipulates the DOM.
👉 To use multiple, wrap elements inside ng-container.
____________________________________________________________________________________

5️⃣ Real-world usage
 • *ngIf for conditional rendering
 • *ngFor for dynamic lists
 • Attribute directives for reusable UI behavior (highlight, permissions, etc.)
____________________________________________________________________________________

🔹Topic: Services & Dependency Injection (DI)

1️⃣ What is a Service in Angular?
A service is a reusable class that contains business logic, API calls, or shared data that can be used across multiple components.
____________________________________________________________________________________

2️⃣ Why do we use Services?
 • Separation of concerns
 • Reusability
 • Cleaner components
 • Easier testing
____________________________________________________________________________________

3️⃣ What is Dependency Injection?
Dependency Injection is a design pattern where Angular provides required dependencies to a class instead of the class creating them.

👉 Angular uses a hierarchical injector system.
____________________________________________________________________________________

4️⃣ What does providedIn: 'root' mean?
It registers the service in the root injector, making it:
 • Singleton
 • Available throughout the app
 • Tree-shakable (better performance)
____________________________________________________________________________________

5️⃣ Difference between providers array and providedIn?
 • providers in component → new instance per component
 • providedIn: 'root' → single global instance
____________________________________________________________________________________

6️⃣ Interview Tip 💡
👉 When would you provide a service at component level?
✔️ When you need isolated state per component instance.

📌 Services + DI are core to scalable Angular architecture.
____________________________________________________________________________________
🔹 Topic: Angular Routing

1️⃣ What is Angular Routing?
Angular Routing enables navigation between different views/components without reloading the page, 
making it a Single Page Application (SPA).
____________________________________________________________________________________

2️⃣ What is RouterModule.forRoot() vs forChild()?
 • forRoot() → used in the root module, creates the main router
 • forChild() → used in feature modules for child routes
____________________________________________________________________________________

3️⃣ What is Lazy Loading in Angular?
Lazy loading loads feature modules only when required, reducing the initial bundle size.

📌 This significantly improves application startup performance.
____________________________________________________________________________________

4️⃣ How do you implement Lazy Loading?
Using loadChildren in route configuration to dynamically import modules.
____________________________________________________________________________________

5️⃣ What are Route Guards?
Route guards control access to routes based on conditions.

Common guards:
 • CanActivate
 • CanDeactivate
 • CanLoad
____________________________________________________________________________________

6️⃣ Interview Tip 💡
👉 Why use CanLoad instead of CanActivate?
✔️ CanLoad prevents lazy modules from even loading, improving security and performance.

📌 Routing & lazy loading are must-know for scalable Angular apps.
____________________________________________________________________________________
Route Guards & Resolvers

🔹 What are Route Guards in Angular?
 Route guards are used to control access to routes based on conditions like authentication or permissions.

🔹 Commonly used Route Guards
 • CanActivate – allows or blocks route navigation
 • CanActivateChild – protects child routes
 • CanDeactivate – prevents leaving a route (unsaved changes)
 • CanLoad – prevents lazy modules from loading
____________________________________________________________________________________
🔹 What is a Resolver?
 A resolver is used to fetch data before a route is activated, ensuring the component loads with required data.

🔹 Guard vs Resolver
 Guards → decide whether navigation is allowed
 Resolvers → decide what data is needed before navigation

🔹 Why are Resolvers useful?
 • Prevent empty UI states
 • Improve user experience
 • Centralize data fetching logic

💡 Interview Tip
 Use CanLoad for secure lazy loading and Resolvers for preloading critical data.
____________________________________________________________________________________

🔹 Topic: Template-Driven vs Reactive Forms

1️⃣ What are Forms in Angular?
Angular forms provide a way to capture user input, validate data, and manage form state.
____________________________________________________________________________________

2️⃣ What is a Template-Driven Form?
 • Logic is mostly in the HTML template
 • Uses ngModel
 • Simple to set up
 • Best for small, simple forms

📌 Less control, harder to test.
____________________________________________________________________________________

3️⃣ What is a Reactive Form?
 • Logic is in the TypeScript component
 • Uses FormControl, FormGroup, FormArray
 • Highly scalable and testable
 • Best for complex and dynamic forms
____________________________________________________________________________________

4️⃣ Key differences interviewers expect

Template-Driven Reactive
Easy to use More control
Less scalable Highly scalable
Harder to test Easy to unit test
Two-way binding Immutable data model
____________________________________________________________________________________

5️⃣ When should you prefer Reactive Forms?
 • Complex validations
 • Dynamic form fields
 • Large enterprise applications

📌 Most production-grade Angular apps rely on Reactive Forms.
____________________________________________________________________________________
🔹 Topic: HttpClient & Interceptors

1️⃣ What is HttpClient in Angular?
 HttpClient is Angular’s built-in service used to communicate with backend APIs using HTTP methods 
 like GET, POST, PUT, and DELETE.
📌 It returns Observables, making it easy to work with RxJS operators.
_____________________________________________________________________________

2️⃣ How does Angular handle HTTP responses?
 Angular automatically:
Converts JSON responses
Provides typed responses using TypeScript generics
Supports intercepting requests and responses
_____________________________________________________________________________

3️⃣ What is an HTTP Interceptor?
 An HTTP Interceptor is used to intercept and modify HTTP requests or responses globally.

Common use cases:
1.Attaching auth tokens
2.Logging requests
3.Global error handling
4.Showing/hiding loaders
_____________________________________________________________________________
4️⃣ Can we have multiple interceptors?
 ✅ Yes.
 Angular supports multiple interceptors, executed in the order they are provided.
_____________________________________________________________________________

5️⃣ Difference between Interceptor and Service?
Service → handles specific API logic
Interceptor → handles cross-cutting concerns across all APIs
_____________________________________________________________________________
6️⃣ Interview Tip 💡
 👉 Where do you add authorization headers?
 ✔️ In an HTTP Interceptor, not inside individual services.
📌 Understanding interceptors shows production-level Angular experience.
_____________________________________________________________________________
Topic: Pipes (Built-in & Custom)

🔹 What is a Pipe in Angular?
 A pipe is used to transform data directly in the template without modifying the original value. It helps keep templates clean and readable.

🔹 Common built-in pipes
 • date
 • currency
 • uppercase / lowercase
 • decimal
 • async
__________________________________________________________________________________________________________
🔹 What is a Custom Pipe?
 A custom pipe allows you to create reusable transformation logic such as formatting values, mapping status labels, or custom display rules.
__________________________________________________________________________________________________________
🔹 Pure vs Impure Pipes
 Pure Pipe (default):
 • Executes only when the input reference changes
 • Better performance
Impure Pipe:
 • Executes on every change detection cycle
 • Can impact performance if not used carefully
_____________________________________________________________________________
🔹 Why is the async pipe important?
 • Automatically subscribes and unsubscribes
 • Prevents memory leaks
 • Works seamlessly with Observables and Promises

💡 Interview Tip
 Avoid heavy business logic inside pipes. Keep complex logic inside services, not templates.
__________________________________________________________________________________________________________

Content Projection & View Encapsulation
Continuing my Angular day-wise interview series, covering concepts that help build reusable and maintainable components.

🔹 What is Content Projection?
 Content projection allows you to pass content from a parent component into a child component using <ng-content>.
It helps in creating reusable and flexible UI components.
__________________________________________________________________________________________________________
🔹 Types of Content Projection
 • Single-slot projection – projects all content into one slot
 • Multi-slot projection – projects content into specific slots using selectors
_____________________________________________________________________________
🔹 Real-world use cases
 • Reusable UI components (cards, modals, tabs)
 • Layout components
 • Design system components
_____________________________________________________________________________
🔹 What is View Encapsulation?
 View encapsulation defines how component styles are scoped and applied.
Angular provides three types:
 • Emulated (default) – styles scoped to the component
 • None – styles applied globally
 • ShadowDom – uses native Shadow DOM
__________________________________________________________________________________________________________

🔹 When should you change encapsulation?
 • Design systems → None or ShadowDom
 • Isolated components → Emulated

💡 Interview Tip
 Content projection is often asked with real examples, not theory. Be ready to explain where you’ve used it.
__________________________________________________________________________________________________________
🔹Topic: RxJS Fundamentals

1️⃣ What is RxJS?
RxJS is a library for reactive programming using Observables, 
used extensively in Angular for handling async operations like HTTP calls and events.
____________________________________________________________________________________

2️⃣ What is an Observable?
An Observable represents a stream of data that can emit:
 • Multiple values
 • Over time
 • Synchronously or asynchronously

👉 Unlike Promises, Observables can emit multiple values and be cancelled.
____________________________________________________________________________________

3️⃣ Observable vs Promise?
 • Observable → lazy, cancellable, multiple values
 • Promise → eager, not cancellable, single value
____________________________________________________________________________________

4️⃣ What is a Subscription?
A Subscription is the execution of an Observable.
You receive data by calling .subscribe().

📌 Subscriptions must be unsubscribed to avoid memory leaks.
____________________________________________________________________________________

5️⃣ How do you handle unsubscription?
 • async pipe (recommended)
 • takeUntil() pattern
 • Unsubscribe in ngOnDestroy()
____________________________________________________________________________________

6️⃣ Interview Tip 💡
👉 Why is async pipe preferred?
✔️ It automatically subscribes and unsubscribes, preventing memory leaks.

📌 RxJS knowledge is mandatory for real-world Angular development.
____________________________________________________________________________________

🔹 Topic: RxJS Mapping Operators

1️⃣ What does map() do?
map() transforms emitted values into new values.

📌 Use case: simple data transformation.
____________________________________________________________________________________

2️⃣ What is switchMap()?
switchMap():
 • Cancels the previous inner observable
 • Switches to the latest one

📌 Best for:
 • Search inputs
 • Auto-complete
 • Type-ahead APIs
____________________________________________________________________________________

3️⃣ What is mergeMap()?
mergeMap():
 • Subscribes to all inner observables
 • Executes them in parallel

📌 Best for:
 • Multiple independent API calls
 • Fire-and-forget operations
____________________________________________________________________________________

4️⃣ Key difference interviewers expect

Operator Cancels previous Parallel Use case
map ❌ ❌ Transform data
switchMap ✅ ❌ Latest request only
mergeMap ❌ ✅ Parallel requests
____________________________________________________________________________________

5️⃣ Common interview trap 💡
👉 Why not always use mergeMap()?
✔️ Because uncontrolled parallel calls can cause race conditions.

📌 Choosing the right operator shows real production experience.
____________________________________________________________________________________